SIMPLE: molar
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: molar
<hw>mo"lar</hw> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧"l⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>moles</ets> mass.]</ety> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining
to a mass of matter; -- said of the properties or motions of masses, as
distinguished from those of molecules or atoms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>molar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: molar
<hw>mo"lar</hw> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧"l⟦etil⟧r <it>or</it> m⟦omac⟧"l⟦aum⟧r)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>moles</ets> mass.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>Being at a concentration having the designated number of moles (of
solute) per liter of solvent; <as>as, an 0.2 <ex>molar</ex> solution of
sodium chloride in water is close to isotonic</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Molar
<hw>Mo"lar</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>molaris</ets>, fr.
<ets>mola</ets> mill, fr. <ets>molere</ets> to grind in a mill. See
<er>Mill</er> the machine.]</ety> <def>Having power to grind; grinding;
<as>as, the <ex>molar</ex> teeth</as>; also, of or pertaining to the
molar teeth.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Molar
<hw>Mo"lar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Any one of the
teeth back of the incisors and canines. The molars which replace the
deciduous or milk teeth are designated as <stype>premolars</stype>, and
those which are not preceded by deciduous teeth are sometimes called
<stype>true molars</stype>. See <er>Tooth</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Molary</ent>⟦br⟧
